<h2>HVAC Systems in New Jersey</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>

<p>New Jersey's humid subtropical to humid continental climate creates significant demands for both heating and cooling systems throughout the year. Summer temperatures regularly reach 80-90¬∞F with high humidity levels that can make conditions feel even hotter, necessitating reliable air conditioning from May through September. Winter temperatures frequently drop below freezing, with average lows in January ranging from 20¬∞F in northern counties to 26¬∞F along the shore, requiring robust heating systems capable of maintaining comfort during extended cold periods.</p>

<p>The state's coastal location moderates temperature extremes but increases humidity levels, making efficient dehumidification an important consideration for HVAC system selection. Heat pumps are increasingly popular in New Jersey due to their ability to provide both heating and cooling efficiently, particularly modern cold-climate heat pumps that maintain performance even during winter temperature drops. The shoulder seasons of spring and fall are relatively mild, providing opportunities for heat pumps to operate at peak efficiency and for homeowners to reduce energy consumption through natural ventilation.</p>

<p>New Jersey's variable weather patterns, including occasional extreme weather events, emphasize the importance of reliable and efficient HVAC systems. The state experiences an average of 1,200-1,400 cooling degree days and 4,500-5,500 heating degree days annually, indicating substantial energy demands for climate control. Modern high-efficiency systems can significantly reduce these energy requirements while providing superior comfort control and indoor air quality improvements.</p>

