<h2>New Jersey Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>New Jersey offers one of the most comprehensive renewable energy incentive packages in the United States, making solar installations and efficient HVAC systems highly attractive investments. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% credit against federal income taxes for the full installed cost of solar panel systems, including equipment, installation, and interconnection fees. This credit has no cap and can be carried forward to future tax years if the credit exceeds the homeowner's tax liability. The 30% credit rate is scheduled to remain in effect through 2032 before stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034.</p>

<p>The state's Solar Renewable Energy Certificate (SREC) program provides ongoing revenue for solar system owners by allowing them to sell certificates representing the environmental benefits of their solar production. Each SREC represents 1,000 kWh of solar electricity generation and can be sold to utilities that need to meet renewable energy portfolio standards. SREC prices in New Jersey have ranged from \$15-45 per certificate in recent years, providing typical homeowners with an additional \$150-450 annually in revenue from an average-sized solar installation. The New Jersey Clean Energy Program administers the SREC market and provides online tools for tracking and selling certificates.</p>

<p>PSE&G offers several rebate programs for energy-efficient HVAC equipment through its Energy Efficiency Programs. Heat pump installations can qualify for rebates of \$300-800 depending on efficiency ratings, while high-efficiency furnaces and central air conditioning systems are eligible for rebates of \$200-500. The utility also provides enhanced rebates for smart thermostats (\$50-100) and whole-house air sealing services (\$500-1,000). Many New Jersey municipalities offer additional property tax exemptions for renewable energy installations, meaning solar panels typically won't increase property tax assessments despite adding significant value to homes. Some utilities also offer time-of-use rate schedules that can maximize savings from solar production by providing higher compensation rates during peak demand periods when solar generation is typically highest.</p>

